05680nam a22008415i 9780812206890DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013947371  a(OCoLC)1029829703  a(OCoLC)979724284  a97808122068907 a10.9783/97808122068902doi  a(DE-B1597)449480  a(OCoLC)794700704  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN2582.W65bN87 2010 7aDRA0030002bisacsh04a792.02/80820941090332221 aNussbaum, Felicity, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRival Queens :bActresses, Performance, and the Eighteenth-Century British Theater /cFelicity Nussbaum. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b29 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: At Stage’s Edge -- tChapter 1. The Economics of Celebrity -- tChapter 2. “Real, Beautiful Women”: Rival Queens -- tChapter 3. Actresses’ Memoirs: Exceptional Virtue -- tChapter 4. Actresses and Patrons: The Theatrical Contract -- tChapter 5. The Actress and Performative Property: Catherine Clive -- tChapter 6. The Actress, Travesty, and Nation: Margaret Woffington -- tChapter 7. The Actress and Material Femininity: Frances Abington -- tEpilogue: Contracted Virtue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn eighteenth-century England, actresses were frequently dismissed as mere prostitutes trading on their sexual power rather than their talents. Yet they were, Felicity Nussbaum argues, central to the success of a newly commercial theater. Urban, recently moneyed, and thoroughly engaged with their audiences, celebrated actresses were among the first women to achieve social mobility, cultural authority, and financial independence. In fact, Nussbaum contends, the eighteenth century might well be called the "age of the actress" in the British theater, given women's influence on the dramatic repertory and, through it, on the definition of femininity.Treating individual star actresses who helped spark a cult of celebrity—especially Anne Oldfield, Susannah Cibber, Catherine Clive, Margaret Woffington, Frances Abington, and George Anne Bellamy—Rival Queens reveals the way these women animated issues of national identity, property, patronage, and fashion in the context of their dramatic performances. Actresses intentionally heightened their commercial appeal by catapulting the rivalries among themselves to center stage. They also boldly challenged in importance the actor-managers who have long dominated eighteenth-century theater history and criticism. Felicity Nussbaum combines an emphasis on the actresses themselves with close analysis of their diverse roles in works by major playwrights, including George Farquhar, Nicholas Rowe, Colley Cibber, Arthur Murphy, David Garrick, Isaac Bickerstaff, and Richard Sheridan. Hers is a comprehensive and original argument about the importance of actresses as the first modern subjects, actively shaping their public identities to make themselves into celebrated properties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aActresseszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aTheater and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomen in the theaterzGreat BritainxHistoryx18th century. 0aWomen in the theaterzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 4aGender Studies. 7aDRAMA / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLiterature.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Co